title: King's brother Andrew released after arrest | ABC NEWS
description: Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor, the brother of King Charles, has been released after he was arrested at his Sandringham home on suspicion of misconduct in public office. Thames Valley Police said officers searched two properties in Berkshire and Norfolk, both believed to be on royal grounds. The king says he is deeply concerned about the arrest and that Buckingham Palace will give its full support to the investigation. title: Annabel Crabb on Andrew’s arrest | ABC News Daily podcast
description: Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor has spent about 10 hours of his 66th birthday in police custody as they investigate whether the former prince shared government secrets with the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein.    King Charles has tried to distance himself from the man who remains eighth in line to the throne. But can the royal family survive this scandal?   Today, the ABC’s Annabel Crabb on what happens when the justice system comes for the King’s brother.   Featured:    Annabel Crabb, ABC writer and presenter

title: ABC views list of 11 Australian women with ISIS links | ABC NEWS
description: The ABC can reveal the names of the 11 women connected to former Islamic State fighters in Syria who attempted to journey home to Australia this week The group of 34 Australians, including 23 children, has been living in camps in Syria since the fall of the so-called caliphate, and some of those children were actually born behind the razor wire. Some of the women are believed to have accompanied their husbands to the war zone, but others came with family and married IS fighters once they arrived. Some say they got stuck in Syria by accident. Many of them have previously spoken to the ABC.  Video by Matthew Doran.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Milano-Cortina: How Alysa Liu reclaimed her joy and turned it in to gold
description: Alysa Liu retired from figure skating four years ago, aged 16, saying she'd lost herself in competition. Fast-forward to the 2026 Olympic Winter Games and she's back with a gold medal around her neck but perhaps more importantly, she did it her way. Team USA had high expectations for their figure skating team in Milan and not everyone could live up to them, so how might the joy of Liu's gold change the way the sport deals with its athletes?   Featured: Caroline Price, journalist, Forbes.    Subscribe to the ABC Sport Newsletter (https://www.abc.net.au/connect)
